WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:10.387 --> 00:00:11.220
SCOTT: Hi, everyone.

00:00:11.220 --> 00:00:12.460
I'm Chef Scott.

00:00:12.460 --> 00:00:16.290
I'm introducing Chef Georg from
the Ojai Valley Inn and Spa.

00:00:16.290 --> 00:00:18.410
He's going to do some
cool stuff for you guys.

00:00:18.410 --> 00:00:19.250
I hope you enjoy.

00:00:19.250 --> 00:00:23.289
And have a good day after that.

00:00:23.289 --> 00:00:24.830
GEORG PAULUSSEN:
The first one, we're

00:00:24.830 --> 00:00:26.550
going to make an appetizer.

00:00:26.550 --> 00:00:28.960
First one, we have a
heirloom tomato salad.

00:00:28.960 --> 00:00:30.580
These ones are
heirloom tomatoes.

00:00:30.580 --> 00:00:32.895
And we have them growing
at the Ojai Valley Inn

00:00:32.895 --> 00:00:34.860
and Spa in our own herb garden.

00:00:34.860 --> 00:00:39.260
And these are tomatoes with
a 5,000 year seed history.

00:00:39.260 --> 00:00:41.430
So they're really, really
cool and very flavorful.

00:00:41.430 --> 00:00:43.760
Many times when you go in
a supermarket-- and people

00:00:43.760 --> 00:00:45.832
who maybe don't know, they
see tomatoes like that

00:00:45.832 --> 00:00:47.020
and it's like, I
don't want to buy it.

00:00:47.020 --> 00:00:49.020
They don't look very
pretty, And all that stuff.

00:00:49.020 --> 00:00:51.960
But these are actually
really good, flavorful, tasty

00:00:51.960 --> 00:00:52.460
tomatoes.

00:00:52.460 --> 00:00:54.170
Then we got some
small ones here.

00:00:54.170 --> 00:00:56.150
These are also grape tomatoes.

00:00:56.150 --> 00:00:57.700
And they're also heirloom.

00:00:57.700 --> 00:00:59.680
Then we got some other
herbs and spices,

00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:01.690
which I'm going to
show you in a second.

00:01:01.690 --> 00:01:04.510
So what we would like
to start-- and we

00:01:04.510 --> 00:01:06.350
don't do this just
for television,

00:01:06.350 --> 00:01:08.420
we're going to put
on some gloves.

00:01:08.420 --> 00:01:11.389
And I believe that even
though-- if you maybe

00:01:11.389 --> 00:01:13.430
cook at home and all that
stuff, it's always good

00:01:13.430 --> 00:01:15.280
if you put your gloves on.

00:01:15.280 --> 00:01:17.642
And then you don't have
no cross contamination.

00:01:17.642 --> 00:01:18.600
All that stuff is good.

00:01:18.600 --> 00:01:20.470
So I've got a couple
of tomatoes here,

00:01:20.470 --> 00:01:24.930
which we're going to slice
in relatively big chunks.

00:01:24.930 --> 00:01:28.804
So if you have six pieces
of a tomato like that.

00:01:28.804 --> 00:01:30.970
And then we want to do a
couple of different colors.

00:01:30.970 --> 00:01:33.800
Now, the flavor
profile is the same.

00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:36.460
What is different is the look.

00:01:36.460 --> 00:01:41.917
And I'll show you how
very different they look.

00:01:47.390 --> 00:01:48.080
See?

00:01:48.080 --> 00:01:50.050
And they're all ripe,
even though maybe they

00:01:50.050 --> 00:01:51.120
have different colors.

00:01:51.120 --> 00:01:52.829
But they all still
have the same texture.

00:01:52.829 --> 00:01:54.869
And they kind of taste
the same, except that they

00:01:54.869 --> 00:01:55.500
look different.

00:01:55.500 --> 00:02:00.230
Some small differences is
maybe the flavor profile.

00:02:00.230 --> 00:02:03.710
Then over here we have
some Meyer lemons.

00:02:03.710 --> 00:02:04.660
Meyer lemons.

00:02:04.660 --> 00:02:07.660
As you can see, these
ones are pixie oranges.

00:02:07.660 --> 00:02:11.210
Meyer lemons are almost
like an orange from the look

00:02:11.210 --> 00:02:14.210
and from the texture of
the skin and the inside,

00:02:14.210 --> 00:02:16.040
except they're a lot sweeter.

00:02:16.040 --> 00:02:18.260
So they're a little
bit a mixture

00:02:18.260 --> 00:02:20.810
between a lemon, a
lime, and an orange.

00:02:20.810 --> 00:02:24.029
Gives a very different
and unique flavor.

00:02:24.029 --> 00:02:25.820
I'm going to squeeze
a little bit in there.

00:02:25.820 --> 00:02:28.610
Unfortunately, they
have about 6,000 seeds,

00:02:28.610 --> 00:02:31.130
so you want to make sure that
you don't get all of them

00:02:31.130 --> 00:02:33.260
in there.

00:02:33.260 --> 00:02:37.080
Just take a little
bit of lemon juice.

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:42.150
Then we have cold pressed
extra virgin olive

00:02:42.150 --> 00:02:47.840
oil, cracked black pepper.

00:02:47.840 --> 00:02:50.285
Very simple.

00:02:50.285 --> 00:02:51.750
And a little bit of salt.

00:02:54.650 --> 00:02:55.950
And then comes the fun part.

00:02:55.950 --> 00:02:57.250
I have a little bit of honey.

00:03:01.330 --> 00:03:02.200
About a tablespoon.

00:03:05.690 --> 00:03:11.470
And what's really nice with the
lemon and the pixie flavor--

00:03:11.470 --> 00:03:13.010
and a little bit of mustard.

00:03:13.010 --> 00:03:14.990
We're going to make a dressing.

00:03:14.990 --> 00:03:18.200
And this dressing
we'll be making here

00:03:18.200 --> 00:03:21.580
is actually part of the
salmon dressing as well.

00:03:24.352 --> 00:03:25.050
So you see?

00:03:25.050 --> 00:03:25.730
Very simple.

00:03:25.730 --> 00:03:27.010
And it emulsifies.

00:03:27.010 --> 00:03:30.940
You want to make sure is that
the olive oil, the honey,

00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:33.690
and all the juices
really going to mix well.

00:03:33.690 --> 00:03:36.970
You take your tomatoes.

00:03:36.970 --> 00:03:41.622
And then you just marinate
them in the dressing

00:03:41.622 --> 00:03:42.330
for a little bit.

00:03:46.105 --> 00:03:46.605
OK.

00:03:49.455 --> 00:03:51.370
There you go.

00:03:51.370 --> 00:03:54.170
Here's one of the short cuts
I was talking about earlier.

00:03:54.170 --> 00:03:56.900
This one is a gravlax.

00:03:56.900 --> 00:04:01.250
And what it is it's basically
a line caught Pacific salmon.

00:04:01.250 --> 00:04:06.300
So it's the one which runs right
outside your waters out here.

00:04:06.300 --> 00:04:08.710
Originally gravlax
means like a grave.

00:04:08.710 --> 00:04:10.480
And it comes from Scandinavia.

00:04:10.480 --> 00:04:12.380
And why is it a grave?

00:04:12.380 --> 00:04:15.230
Yesterday, exactly
24 hours ago, I

00:04:15.230 --> 00:04:17.260
made a mix out of
salt and sugar.

00:04:17.260 --> 00:04:18.790
Equal parts.

00:04:18.790 --> 00:04:21.440
I put juniper berries in
there, dill, black pepper,

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:24.980
a little bit of lemon juice,
and Worcestershire sauce.

00:04:24.980 --> 00:04:27.080
I made that mix and put
the salmon in there.

00:04:27.080 --> 00:04:29.560
And, as you can
see, overnight it

00:04:29.560 --> 00:04:34.170
has basically taken out all the
natural juices of the salmon.

00:04:34.170 --> 00:04:36.359
And as you all know,
there's ceviche.

00:04:36.359 --> 00:04:38.025
It's all this kind
of stuff out the way,

00:04:38.025 --> 00:04:41.400
you actually marinate them
with lemon and/or with spices.

00:04:41.400 --> 00:04:44.160
This one is a different
kind from Scandinavia.

00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:47.380
And the flavor profile comes
from the dill and the salt.

00:04:47.380 --> 00:04:49.550
And it does the same
thing like a ceviche.

00:04:49.550 --> 00:04:51.680
Just from a different
part of the world where

00:04:51.680 --> 00:04:55.316
they have used them in a
different pickling way.

00:04:55.316 --> 00:04:57.190
So this salmon, even
though it's not cooked--

00:04:57.190 --> 00:04:59.570
and you get to taste
it in a second--

00:04:59.570 --> 00:05:02.040
feels and looks cooked.

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:03.360
It's very, very delicious.

00:05:03.360 --> 00:05:06.490
And it has changed the color
because it has taken out

00:05:06.490 --> 00:05:08.030
all the natural juices.

00:05:08.030 --> 00:05:10.220
And even just to show
you the back-- see that?

00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:11.610
It's completely cooked.

00:05:11.610 --> 00:05:13.580
Now the disadvantage
you have with something

00:05:13.580 --> 00:05:16.020
like that-- if you leave it
in for longer than 24 hours

00:05:16.020 --> 00:05:17.560
it becomes really salty.

00:05:17.560 --> 00:05:18.690
Very, very strong.

00:05:18.690 --> 00:05:21.395
And the saltier it
becomes, it's better

00:05:21.395 --> 00:05:23.790
if you have the
juice of the lemon,

00:05:23.790 --> 00:05:26.350
or the orange or a little bit
of lime and a little bit honey

00:05:26.350 --> 00:05:29.760
because it counterfeits the
salty taste of the salmon.

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:31.080
So you'll see that in a second.

00:05:31.080 --> 00:05:31.621
We have more.

00:05:31.621 --> 00:05:32.830
Just wash this off please.

00:05:44.180 --> 00:05:46.230
So we have the
tomatoes marinated.

00:05:46.230 --> 00:05:48.130
You can do that
obviously a la minute,

00:05:48.130 --> 00:05:51.110
which it means we'll do it right
now, right here for your guests

00:05:51.110 --> 00:05:52.550
at home or for yourself.

00:05:52.550 --> 00:05:54.630
You marinate a little
bit of salmon--

00:05:54.630 --> 00:05:56.375
a little bit of
tomatoes, pardon me.

00:05:56.375 --> 00:06:02.620
And then over here I have
some pre-washed gem lettuce.

00:06:02.620 --> 00:06:05.700
Gem lettuce is a different
kind of romaine bibb lettuce.

00:06:05.700 --> 00:06:07.620
It's very small, very unique.

00:06:07.620 --> 00:06:11.960
And it has a very
small, delicate flavor.

00:06:11.960 --> 00:06:14.230
And we'll just use
the heart of it.

00:06:14.230 --> 00:06:15.850
And we'll use that as a garnish.

00:06:15.850 --> 00:06:17.890
Every time you use a
lettuce, or every time you

00:06:17.890 --> 00:06:19.469
use a tomato,
cucumber, whatever it

00:06:19.469 --> 00:06:21.510
is, you want to give it
a little bit of dressing.

00:06:21.510 --> 00:06:23.120
It's not too much.

00:06:23.120 --> 00:06:24.230
And mix it all up.

00:06:35.354 --> 00:06:36.770
If you have
questions, just shoot.

00:06:36.770 --> 00:06:38.320
We don't need to
wait until the end.

00:06:38.320 --> 00:06:39.690
If you want to know something.

00:06:39.690 --> 00:06:40.920
So please go ahead.

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:42.375
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:06:42.375 --> 00:06:43.250
GEORG PAULUSSEN: Yes.

00:06:43.250 --> 00:06:46.010
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:06:46.010 --> 00:06:47.330
GEORG PAULUSSEN: You can.

00:06:47.330 --> 00:06:47.907
You can.

00:06:47.907 --> 00:06:49.490
You don't necessarily
need to do that.

00:06:49.490 --> 00:06:51.800
The challenge is when you
do do that, you squeeze out

00:06:51.800 --> 00:06:53.630
the juices much faster.

00:06:53.630 --> 00:06:56.960
And it doesn't take the flavor
of the actual salt and sugar

00:06:56.960 --> 00:06:58.150
mixture.

00:06:58.150 --> 00:07:02.220
If you let it do it gradually
and slowly its own marinade,

00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:04.210
then you get the flavor
all the way through.

00:07:04.210 --> 00:07:07.820
Because if you imagine the
salmon is being squished

00:07:07.820 --> 00:07:10.220
together, you have
no room to breathe,

00:07:10.220 --> 00:07:11.290
even though you're dead.

00:07:11.290 --> 00:07:12.998
But it doesn't go
through it all the way.

00:07:15.640 --> 00:07:17.610
So we got the dead
salmon right here.

00:07:17.610 --> 00:07:18.780
He's still all very happy.

00:07:18.780 --> 00:07:21.310
And he's all
delicious right now.

00:07:21.310 --> 00:07:25.030
And I'm going to cut
straight through the center.

00:07:25.030 --> 00:07:26.780
You have seen from the
top, from the back.

00:07:26.780 --> 00:07:28.950
And look how
beautiful that looks.

00:07:28.950 --> 00:07:30.150
And it's very easy.

00:07:30.150 --> 00:07:31.570
It's very delicate.

00:07:31.570 --> 00:07:37.824
And it's very, should I
say, very easy to slice.

00:07:37.824 --> 00:07:39.240
Let me make a
little bit of space.

00:07:39.240 --> 00:07:42.492
I want to make sure
you can see this.

00:07:42.492 --> 00:07:44.005
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:44.005 --> 00:07:44.880
GEORG PAULUSSEN: Yes.

00:07:44.880 --> 00:07:46.420
Yes, you would refrigerate it.

00:07:51.850 --> 00:07:53.930
So there's different
ways of slicing it.

00:07:53.930 --> 00:07:57.795
You can slice it
straight through.

00:07:57.795 --> 00:08:00.030
For our purpose, for
our presentation,

00:08:00.030 --> 00:08:01.260
I like to do it like this.

00:08:01.260 --> 00:08:07.330
Or you slice it-- if you want
to make a nice gravlax bagel

00:08:07.330 --> 00:08:10.390
sandwich in the
morning or something,

00:08:10.390 --> 00:08:11.880
then you slice it like this.

00:08:18.210 --> 00:08:23.110
What is important as you slice
not just this, as you slice

00:08:23.110 --> 00:08:26.020
anything at home, let
the knife do the work.

00:08:26.020 --> 00:08:28.520
Don't let your elbows-- don't
let your arm do the work.

00:08:28.520 --> 00:08:31.740
Let the knife flow
through your product.

00:08:31.740 --> 00:08:34.400
And as you can see, if you can
read a newspaper through it,

00:08:34.400 --> 00:08:35.309
you did a good job.

00:08:35.309 --> 00:08:36.610
That's how thin
it's supposed to be.

00:08:36.610 --> 00:08:38.539
If it's thicker, it's
not going to taste good.

00:08:38.539 --> 00:08:41.272
So the more newspaper you can
read, the happier you will be.

00:08:41.272 --> 00:08:42.200
All right.

00:08:42.200 --> 00:08:45.470
So we take a little
bit of salmon.

00:08:45.470 --> 00:08:48.420
Make sure there
are no bones in it.

00:08:57.654 --> 00:09:02.700
And, again, if you
don't like salmon,

00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:06.450
or if you like a different kind
of fish-- you like halibut,

00:09:06.450 --> 00:09:09.070
you like tuna-- you can do it
with all these kinds of fish.

00:09:09.070 --> 00:09:10.976
You can do it the same way.

00:09:10.976 --> 00:09:13.360
A different marinade from Asia.

00:09:13.360 --> 00:09:15.690
I used to work in
Japan for many years.

00:09:15.690 --> 00:09:19.780
In Asia and Japan they do
the same style with a salmon

00:09:19.780 --> 00:09:22.910
or with a tuna, but you would
use soya sauce and ginger

00:09:22.910 --> 00:09:24.640
and garlic and chili peppers.

00:09:24.640 --> 00:09:26.420
So wherever you go
around the world,

00:09:26.420 --> 00:09:29.930
the principal of a
marinated fish is the same,

00:09:29.930 --> 00:09:33.390
but the flavor profile
is completely different.

00:09:33.390 --> 00:09:36.765
So now we have these
marinated tomatoes.

00:09:45.078 --> 00:09:49.330
As you can see,
what's really nice is

00:09:49.330 --> 00:09:53.392
the contrast of the
different colors.

00:09:53.392 --> 00:09:57.070
We have a couple of pieces
of a little gem lettuce.

00:10:01.650 --> 00:10:04.630
And then we take a couple of--
make sure all of this stuff

00:10:04.630 --> 00:10:07.122
is washed.

00:10:07.122 --> 00:10:08.580
We got enough
protein on the plate.

00:10:08.580 --> 00:10:09.955
We don't want more
protein on it.

00:10:24.253 --> 00:10:24.760
OK.

00:10:24.760 --> 00:10:29.502
And then you see the
dressing is still emulsified.

00:10:29.502 --> 00:10:32.165
Take a little bit of that.

00:10:32.165 --> 00:10:33.040
Put it on the salmon.

00:10:35.870 --> 00:10:36.930
And how fast was that?

00:10:36.930 --> 00:10:38.888
Now if we forget about
that little sucker which

00:10:38.888 --> 00:10:42.710
is 24 hours old, this
was relatively fast.

00:10:42.710 --> 00:10:44.510
That was five
minutes, 10 minutes.

00:10:44.510 --> 00:10:46.880
And you have a really cool,
great looking appetizer.

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:48.480
It's always coming
down in a kitchen.

00:10:48.480 --> 00:10:49.840
We talk about mise en place.

00:10:49.840 --> 00:10:53.860
Mise en place is the production,
which is in its place

00:10:53.860 --> 00:10:54.607
before we start.

00:10:54.607 --> 00:10:56.190
Once you have all
this stuff lined up,

00:10:56.190 --> 00:10:57.610
it's going to go really fast.

00:10:57.610 --> 00:10:59.722
So what I'll do, I'll
slice a few more pieces

00:10:59.722 --> 00:11:01.930
and then Moe is going to
give you some sample plates.

00:11:01.930 --> 00:11:04.340
And you guys can take
five minutes or something

00:11:04.340 --> 00:11:05.340
to taste it.

00:11:05.340 --> 00:11:07.810
And then I'm going to go
and start the next course.

00:11:07.810 --> 00:11:08.975
Sounds good?

00:11:08.975 --> 00:11:11.060
All right.

00:11:11.060 --> 00:11:11.935
So now is the music.

00:11:11.935 --> 00:11:12.685
Where's the music?

00:11:17.360 --> 00:11:19.401
Make me work for a living here.

00:11:19.401 --> 00:11:19.900
OK.

00:11:19.900 --> 00:11:20.890
More.

00:11:20.890 --> 00:11:21.570
You ready?

00:11:29.370 --> 00:11:31.520
Any other questions?

00:11:31.520 --> 00:11:35.234
I only look like a chef,
but I'm not that mean.

00:11:35.234 --> 00:11:36.150
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:11:38.312 --> 00:11:39.270
GEORG PAULUSSEN: I see.

00:11:39.270 --> 00:11:42.050
Now you had to do that.

00:11:42.050 --> 00:11:42.670
Who said that?

00:11:42.670 --> 00:11:43.900
I wasn't looking up.

00:11:43.900 --> 00:11:44.805
Just kidding.

00:11:44.805 --> 00:11:46.320
I'm from Germany.

00:11:46.320 --> 00:11:47.990
I was born and
raised in Germany.

00:11:47.990 --> 00:11:51.050
And I left the
country when I was

00:11:51.050 --> 00:11:53.970
22-years-old to work
on a cruise ship.

00:11:53.970 --> 00:11:58.930
And some of you younger
folks maybe don't know,

00:11:58.930 --> 00:12:01.620
but you used to have a
television show in the US.

00:12:01.620 --> 00:12:03.180
It was called "The Love Boat."

00:12:03.180 --> 00:12:05.690
And we had the same
thing in Germany.

00:12:05.690 --> 00:12:07.040
The German "Love Boat."

00:12:07.040 --> 00:12:08.120
And I joined that one.

00:12:08.120 --> 00:12:10.620
It was the first time
when I actually left

00:12:10.620 --> 00:12:13.610
my village where I came from.

00:12:13.610 --> 00:12:14.650
And I liked it so much.

00:12:14.650 --> 00:12:18.320
And I said, wow, I get to be
able to see the whole world.

00:12:18.320 --> 00:12:19.330
And I get paid for it.

00:12:19.330 --> 00:12:24.020
So I left and I never
went back-- only to visit.

00:12:24.020 --> 00:12:24.675
OK.

00:12:24.675 --> 00:12:25.415
Here we go.

00:12:31.440 --> 00:12:33.720
I started in Germany.

00:12:33.720 --> 00:12:37.570
And then from Germany, my
first outside the country job

00:12:37.570 --> 00:12:39.140
was New York.

00:12:39.140 --> 00:12:44.110
And I've said that
story before when--

00:12:44.110 --> 00:12:45.510
let me start it a different way.

00:12:45.510 --> 00:12:47.360
I started in Germany.

00:12:47.360 --> 00:12:48.400
I did my apprenticeship.

00:12:48.400 --> 00:12:50.460
I did my whole stuff
with "The Love Boat."

00:12:50.460 --> 00:12:51.510
And then I came to US.

00:12:51.510 --> 00:12:53.940
And we had 1,500 people
living in my village.

00:12:53.940 --> 00:12:55.420
So that's how small it was.

00:12:55.420 --> 00:12:58.750
And I went to a city in New
York with 15 million people.

00:12:58.750 --> 00:13:00.460
I didn't speak a
word of English.

00:13:00.460 --> 00:13:01.580
Hi, hello, that was it.

00:13:01.580 --> 00:13:03.850
That's all I could say
for the first six months.

00:13:03.850 --> 00:13:07.489
And I started learning English
on watching "Wheel of Fortune."

00:13:07.489 --> 00:13:10.030
I couldn't answer a single thing
about what they were saying,

00:13:10.030 --> 00:13:12.945
but I was listening to the
letters, the pronunciation,

00:13:12.945 --> 00:13:14.680
the ABC, and all that stuff.

00:13:14.680 --> 00:13:16.635
And eventually it
started making sense.

00:13:16.635 --> 00:13:18.260
And then like you do
in every language,

00:13:18.260 --> 00:13:20.460
the first thing I
knew was how to cuss

00:13:20.460 --> 00:13:21.830
in New York, and all that stuff.

00:13:21.830 --> 00:13:24.160
How to talk bad
language, especially

00:13:24.160 --> 00:13:27.770
in the kitchen, as you know--
well, maybe as you have heard.

00:13:27.770 --> 00:13:28.530
So I did this.

00:13:28.530 --> 00:13:30.740
And then from New
York I went to London,

00:13:30.740 --> 00:13:32.710
worked in London for
one and a half years.

00:13:32.710 --> 00:13:35.470
Came back to New York, and I
worked in New York and Boston,

00:13:35.470 --> 00:13:37.810
and then left the
US for four years

00:13:37.810 --> 00:13:40.640
to go to work in Tokyo, Japan.

00:13:40.640 --> 00:13:43.820
Worked also with a couple of
stints in New Delhi, India

00:13:43.820 --> 00:13:46.270
and in Hong Kong, Singapore.

00:13:46.270 --> 00:13:48.000
Then I was tired of Asia.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:52.120
Came back to the US and worked
in '97 with Caesar's Palace

00:13:52.120 --> 00:13:54.500
in Las Vegas, was then
the Executive Chef

00:13:54.500 --> 00:13:57.570
at the Venetian in Las Vegas,
worked there for two years

00:13:57.570 --> 00:14:01.700
and left the US again and went
to the Atlantis in the Bahamas.

00:14:01.700 --> 00:14:03.630
And I worked there
for three years.

00:14:03.630 --> 00:14:07.570
And then from Bahamas, I
went back to Las Vegas,

00:14:07.570 --> 00:14:09.020
worked there for
seven years, had

00:14:09.020 --> 00:14:10.850
my own restaurant
and catering company.

00:14:10.850 --> 00:14:15.447
And then as the whole economy
went down, I went down.

00:14:15.447 --> 00:14:16.780
I mean, business is still alive.

00:14:16.780 --> 00:14:17.780
So that's all good.

00:14:17.780 --> 00:14:20.340
But I sold the business.

00:14:20.340 --> 00:14:23.320
And then after
that, I went to work

00:14:23.320 --> 00:14:26.010
for Trump International
in Las Vegas.

00:14:26.010 --> 00:14:29.570
And then I went one year
to the cold in Kansas City.

00:14:29.570 --> 00:14:30.850
And I didn't like that.

00:14:30.850 --> 00:14:32.370
And now I'm finally
in California,

00:14:32.370 --> 00:14:35.090
where I believe I belong,
where I'm the happiest.

00:14:35.090 --> 00:14:37.700
It's kind of like home where
I come from in Germany.

00:14:37.700 --> 00:14:40.650
I mean, obviously, we
don't have an ocean

00:14:40.650 --> 00:14:42.020
like you have over here.

00:14:42.020 --> 00:14:43.480
We got the cold North Sea.

00:14:43.480 --> 00:14:45.510
And it's really gray,
and that's pretty.

00:14:45.510 --> 00:14:47.568
But we got the mountains
and everything else.

