00:15:27.590 --> 00:15:29.331
There's a shiny, but there's
a little bit more shiny

00:15:29.331 --> 00:15:29.914
in the middle.

00:15:29.914 --> 00:15:32.760
The one in the middle,
all the way in the center,

00:15:32.760 --> 00:15:37.000
is the sharpest, hardest
steel of all four of them.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:40.550
But by having it like this,
you have a really great balance

00:15:40.550 --> 00:15:41.720
when you cut with the knife.

00:15:41.720 --> 00:15:44.325
And it stays sharper much
longer than a traditional knife.

00:15:44.325 --> 00:15:46.160
And if you do want
to sharpen it,

00:15:46.160 --> 00:15:48.200
you get it sharp
much, much faster.

00:15:48.200 --> 00:15:51.281
You pull it over
a steel like this.

00:15:51.281 --> 00:15:53.530
And if you know what you're
doing, you do it this way.

00:15:53.530 --> 00:15:55.160
And if you don't,
you do it this way.

00:15:55.160 --> 00:15:57.368
And there are many different
ways and all that stuff.

00:15:57.368 --> 00:16:00.080
But with a regular,
cheaper knife

00:16:00.080 --> 00:16:03.310
you can get in the supermarket,
you do this two or three times

00:16:03.310 --> 00:16:05.707
and you have small little
ridges in the knife.

00:16:05.707 --> 00:16:07.540
And, all of a sudden,
when you cut something

00:16:07.540 --> 00:16:09.422
it rips the meat
or the vegetables

00:16:09.422 --> 00:16:10.380
