00:16:53.235 --> 00:16:57.670
Next one on our menu,
we have a halibut.

00:16:57.670 --> 00:17:02.900
And, again, I really believe
in marinating our seafood.

00:17:02.900 --> 00:17:06.290
We got a nice, fresh
piece of halibut.

00:17:06.290 --> 00:17:12.720
And we are going to
use a pixie orange.

00:17:15.300 --> 00:17:16.339
They only grow in Ojai.

00:17:16.339 --> 00:17:18.470
I don't know if you know that.

00:17:18.470 --> 00:17:23.069
And they only grow within
the first part of spring.

00:17:23.069 --> 00:17:28.430
And they have a slight
sour, orangey flavor.

00:17:28.430 --> 00:17:30.860
So we got some more lemon juice.

00:17:30.860 --> 00:17:35.385
We got this beautiful
pixie flavor.

00:17:39.386 --> 00:17:44.243
And we have some cracked black
pepper and, of course, salt.

00:17:48.570 --> 00:17:50.580
And what I like to
use for this one

00:17:50.580 --> 00:17:54.530
is about a tablespoon
of Worcestershire sauce.

00:17:57.080 --> 00:17:59.234
Just marinate it a little bit.

00:17:59.234 --> 00:18:00.650
And if you do this
at home you can

00:18:00.650 --> 00:18:04.050
put this in the refrigerator
for about an hour or two.

00:18:04.050 --> 00:18:06.380
And just let it rest.

00:18:06.380 --> 00:18:09.360
The best thing is like
seafood, or meat, or something,

00:18:09.360 --> 00:18:11.980
if you let it slightly come
up to room temperature.

00:18:11.980 --> 00:18:13.910
When it's too cold,
it takes too long

00:18:13.910 --> 00:18:16.287
for the outside temperature
to get to the center.

00:18:16.287 --> 00:18:17.870
And by the time it
gets to the center,

00:18:17.870 --> 00:18:19.689
the outside is overcooked.

00:18:19.689 --> 00:18:21.230
So if you have it
at room temperature

00:18:21.230 --> 00:18:23.260
it's very easy for the
steak, for the meat,

00:18:23.260 --> 00:18:27.140
or whatever you want to use,
for evenly the temperature

00:18:27.140 --> 00:18:29.260
to develop.

00:18:29.260 --> 00:18:34.630
We have just a regular pan here
with some extra virgin olive

00:18:34.630 --> 00:18:35.130
oil.

00:18:49.250 --> 00:18:53.030
And under normal circumstances,
meaning normal circumstances

00:18:53.030 --> 00:18:54.840
at home or in a
professional kitchen,

00:18:54.840 --> 00:18:56.980
I would have a big
baking oven behind me.

00:18:56.980 --> 00:19:00.680
I would take the halibut
now, and I would sear it off.

00:19:00.680 --> 00:19:02.360
It's not hot yet.

00:19:02.360 --> 00:19:03.966
Would sear it off
from all four sides

00:19:03.966 --> 00:19:05.590
because it's kind of
like a square log.

00:19:05.590 --> 00:19:08.070
If it's only two sides,
you take from two sides.

00:19:08.070 --> 00:19:11.540
And I would finish it in the
oven on the high temperature.

00:19:11.540 --> 00:19:13.320
And the best is in
a convection oven

00:19:13.320 --> 00:19:15.260
because the temperature
flows around it.

00:19:15.260 --> 00:19:17.230
Keeps the outside
nice, closed up.

00:19:17.230 --> 00:19:18.340
The pores can't run out.

00:19:18.340 --> 00:19:19.830
And it stays juicy.

00:19:19.830 --> 00:19:20.870
All right.

00:19:20.870 --> 00:19:26.080
So with this one we're going
to sear off the halibut.

00:19:26.080 --> 00:19:29.670
And then in the meantime,
we're going to start something

00:19:29.670 --> 00:19:32.760
where it's called a Hollandaise.

00:19:32.760 --> 00:19:37.280
A Hollandaise is a
traditional butter sauce.

00:19:37.280 --> 00:19:41.220
And for this particular one,
I am going to use egg yolk.

00:19:46.770 --> 00:19:49.806
I use white wine.

00:19:49.806 --> 00:19:53.200
Maybe some hot water.

00:19:53.200 --> 00:19:56.465
Then we are going to use
a little bit of Tabasco.

00:19:59.660 --> 00:20:02.270
Again a tick of
Worcestershire sauce.

00:20:06.560 --> 00:20:07.270
A lemon.

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:19.070
And you will see that once I
have seared off the halibut,

00:20:19.070 --> 00:20:21.410
I'm going to put in
some fresh butter.

00:20:21.410 --> 00:20:23.850
The fresh butter, even
though it makes it crispy,

00:20:23.850 --> 00:20:26.350
it keeps it nice and moist.

00:20:26.350 --> 00:20:29.640
And we're also going to
put in some fresh thyme

00:20:29.640 --> 00:20:31.190
and a little bit
of fresh oregano.

00:20:31.190 --> 00:20:32.790
Why fresh thyme and oregano?

00:20:32.790 --> 00:20:34.260
Because we're having
some potatoes.

00:20:34.260 --> 00:20:35.760
These potatoes are
being right now--

00:20:35.760 --> 00:20:37.370
because of time
constraints they're

00:20:37.370 --> 00:20:39.170
being roasted in
the oven right now.

00:20:39.170 --> 00:20:41.790
And we're going to season
all of this together.

00:20:41.790 --> 00:20:48.250
So we have here the egg yolk,
white wine, lemon juice mixed.

00:20:48.250 --> 00:20:51.170
And the traditional way
of making a Hollandaise,

00:20:51.170 --> 00:20:52.650
you make it with tarragon.

00:20:52.650 --> 00:20:55.110
But today we don't
want to do traditional.

00:20:55.110 --> 00:20:57.140
We want to use some dill.

00:20:57.140 --> 00:21:02.319
And because of the application
we use-- bless you--

00:21:02.319 --> 00:21:04.110
we're going to use a
little bit of mustard.

00:21:16.920 --> 00:21:17.890
So it has a nice color.

00:21:24.460 --> 00:21:26.460
And now what I'll do,
I'll put a piece of butter

00:21:26.460 --> 00:21:28.272
in there to let it melt.

00:21:28.272 --> 00:21:29.980
Why I don't put the
butter in right away?

00:21:29.980 --> 00:21:31.930
It's going to burn before.

00:21:31.930 --> 00:21:35.810
So that's why I'm going
to sear off the seafood,

00:21:35.810 --> 00:21:39.430
or steak, or poultry,
whatever you like at home,

00:21:39.430 --> 00:21:40.189
with some oil.

00:21:40.189 --> 00:21:41.730
And then you put
the butter in there,

00:21:41.730 --> 00:21:43.430
and it makes it nice and foamy.

00:21:43.430 --> 00:21:46.190
And then you want to take a
little bit of fresh thyme.

00:21:46.190 --> 00:21:50.070
You don't need to
chop the thyme.

00:21:50.070 --> 00:21:55.441
And you can hear that
really nice crushing sound.

00:21:55.441 --> 00:21:55.940
See?

00:22:00.120 --> 00:22:03.550
And put it a little
bit on this side.

00:22:03.550 --> 00:22:10.682
And you are ready to
flip the fish over.

00:22:10.682 --> 00:22:12.140
And, again, as I
was saying before,

00:22:12.140 --> 00:22:15.240
now would be the time
you put it in the oven.

00:22:19.443 --> 00:22:25.150
And let the temperature
slowly seep through.

00:22:25.150 --> 00:22:28.070
Cover it up.

00:22:28.070 --> 00:22:28.980
And now work with me.

00:22:28.980 --> 00:22:29.764
Zzz.

00:22:29.764 --> 00:22:30.430
Here's the oven.

00:22:30.430 --> 00:22:30.710
And put it in.

00:22:30.710 --> 00:22:31.290
And done.

00:22:31.290 --> 00:22:31.530
OK.

00:22:31.530 --> 00:22:32.190
Good.

00:22:32.190 --> 00:22:32.970
All right.

00:22:32.970 --> 00:22:35.500
So clean up the oven.

00:22:35.500 --> 00:22:39.610
In the meantime, I'm going
to put this on the side.

00:22:39.610 --> 00:22:41.930
We're going to start
our sauce Hollandaise.

00:22:48.956 --> 00:22:52.044
Can you give me a
little hot water?

00:22:52.044 --> 00:22:53.393
Hot water.

00:22:53.393 --> 00:22:53.892
Hot water.

00:22:53.892 --> 00:22:55.986
You got some?

00:22:55.986 --> 00:22:57.023
No, not in there.

00:22:57.023 --> 00:22:57.522
Just in a--

00:23:01.140 --> 00:23:03.350
What's important is
with the Hollandaise,

00:23:03.350 --> 00:23:06.990
that you don't take the
egg and the egg white

00:23:06.990 --> 00:23:09.470
and put it straight
on a hot stove.

00:23:09.470 --> 00:23:11.887
What's going to happen, it's
going to make scrambled eggs.

00:23:11.887 --> 00:23:13.886
So we want to put a little
bit of water in there

00:23:13.886 --> 00:23:15.540
and make it kind of
like a steam bath.

00:23:15.540 --> 00:23:18.525
Then we start whipping
the egg white like this.

00:23:27.571 --> 00:23:30.070
That's the job for apprentices
in the kitchen when they just

00:23:30.070 --> 00:23:30.830
start.

00:23:30.830 --> 00:23:34.200
When you give them to make
a Hollandaise with 400 eggs,

00:23:34.200 --> 00:23:36.530
it's going to take a few hours.

00:23:36.530 --> 00:23:39.184
Well, at that time they
look like your old Governor

00:23:39.184 --> 00:23:40.767
Schwarzenegger, or
somebody like that.

00:23:44.590 --> 00:23:46.420
So it goes relatively fast.

00:23:46.420 --> 00:23:51.826
As soon as the water
is hot it starts--

00:23:51.826 --> 00:23:53.450
and I'll show you
the different stages.

00:23:53.450 --> 00:23:55.710
You see, it starts foaming.

00:23:55.710 --> 00:24:00.330
And you want to whip the base
of your Hollandaise up to a rose

00:24:00.330 --> 00:24:02.940
And what I mean by a rose--
and I'll show in a second.

00:24:02.940 --> 00:24:05.520
You take a wooden spoon or
you take a regular spoon,

00:24:05.520 --> 00:24:08.190
and you take the back of the
spoon and you blow on it.

00:24:08.190 --> 00:24:10.600
Once you blow on it and it
starts to look like a rose,

00:24:10.600 --> 00:24:14.950
that means it has enough cooked
the egg yolk and the egg white.

00:24:14.950 --> 00:24:20.130
And all the flavors emulsified
enough to receive the butter.

00:24:20.130 --> 00:24:22.210
And we use clarified butter.

00:24:22.210 --> 00:24:24.820
If you would use regular
butter, straight melted,

00:24:24.820 --> 00:24:27.680
it has too much
water content in it.

00:24:27.680 --> 00:24:30.090
And it would break
your Hollandaise.

00:24:30.090 --> 00:24:33.140
So what we do, we bring
the butter to a boil

00:24:33.140 --> 00:24:37.880
and let the water, so
to speak, and the milk

00:24:37.880 --> 00:24:41.099
processes sink to the
bottom of the butter.

00:24:41.099 --> 00:24:41.640
You see this?

00:24:41.640 --> 00:24:42.920
How thick this got?

00:24:42.920 --> 00:24:45.260
How fast?

00:24:45.260 --> 00:24:46.102
All right.

00:24:46.102 --> 00:24:48.310
Now what you want to do is,
you want to take it down.

00:24:48.310 --> 00:24:50.166
You don't want to
keep on whipping it

00:24:50.166 --> 00:24:51.915
under too much temperature
because then we

00:24:51.915 --> 00:24:55.790
can still going to end
up with scrambled eggs.

00:24:55.790 --> 00:24:57.002
So that's good.

00:24:59.806 --> 00:25:00.306
OK.

00:25:00.306 --> 00:25:06.539
Now I'll show you what it
means blowing into a rose.

00:25:06.539 --> 00:25:08.080
And I'm going to
put that spoon back.

00:25:08.080 --> 00:25:10.496
I don't want you guys to say,
oh, he's blowing in my food.

00:25:13.225 --> 00:25:14.600
I don't know if
you can see this.

00:25:14.600 --> 00:25:18.380
But when you blow it,
it gets these ridges.

00:25:18.380 --> 00:25:19.650
And it looks like a rose.

00:25:19.650 --> 00:25:22.600
And you see it's
sticking to the spoon.

00:25:22.600 --> 00:25:26.110
Now if you use too
much clarified butter,

00:25:26.110 --> 00:25:26.860
it will break.

00:25:30.130 --> 00:25:32.372
So what you want
to do is you want

00:25:32.372 --> 00:25:33.580
to either do it by the spoon.

00:25:33.580 --> 00:25:37.050
If you're by yourself, you
can do a spoon at a time.

00:25:37.050 --> 00:25:41.630
And if you know what you're
doing, you can pour it in.

00:25:41.630 --> 00:25:44.515
And your bowl comes to life.

00:25:47.150 --> 00:25:48.450
Thank you.

00:25:48.450 --> 00:25:48.980
Thank you.

00:25:48.980 --> 00:25:50.130
Very, very slow.

00:25:50.130 --> 00:25:53.820
If you do it too fast your
